\fs32 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 The isochronous problem explained simply: Isochronous transfers are designed to drop packets if they're late (real-time data that arrives late is useless). TCP is designed to\'a0
\f1\i never
\f0\i0 \'a0drop packets \'97 it retransmits everything. These two philosophies conflict fundamentally. Network jitter as small as 1-2ms can cause VHCI to miss isochronous scheduling windows, producing dropped frames, audio crackle, or device disconnection.\cf5 \cb1 \strokec5 \
