\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ## 1. PRODUCT DESCRIPTION\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 UnisonBridge is a cross-platform, open-source USB device orchestration platform that\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 enables physical USB devices attached to any machine on a network to be shared,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 managed, and consumed by any other machine on that network \'97 as if the device were\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 physically plugged in locally. The platform operates through three tightly integrated\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 layers: a lightweight Agent daemon that runs on every participating machine, a central\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 Orchestration Server that maintains the global network topology and coordinates all\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 connections, and a responsive web-based dashboard that presents the entire USB\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 ecosystem in a single view with drag-and-drop device assignment, real-time log\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 streaming, device compatibility analysis, and virtual device management.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 The platform is built on top of the open USB/IP protocol \'97 a kernel-level mechanism\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 that encapsulates USB Request Blocks (URBs) into TCP/IP packets, merged into the Linux\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 kernel at version 3.17 \'97 and extends it with cross-platform agents for Windows (via\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 dorssel/usbipd-win and vadimgrn/usbip-win2) and macOS (via VirtualHere integration),\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 automatic network discovery using mDNS/DNS-SD, a protocol abstraction layer that\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 intelligently falls back from USB/IP to GStreamer, PipeWire, or VirtualHere when a\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 device's isochronous transfer requirements cannot be satisfied by TCP-based tunneling,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 and a virtual device layer that allows audio sinks, video cameras, and HID devices to\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 be created entirely in software and shared as though they were physical hardware.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 UnisonBridge fills a gap that no existing open-source tool addresses: the combination\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 of unified cross-platform orchestration, protocol-aware fallback, virtual device\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 creation, mDNS zero-config discovery, real-time compatibility scoring before connection\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 attempts, and a web UI with audit logging, RBAC, and structured diagnostics. Commercial\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 alternatives such as VirtualHere ($49/server), FlexiHub (subscription), and USB\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 Network Gate (per-device licensing) solve pieces of this problem but are closed-source,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 expensive at scale, and do not expose the orchestration API or allow self-hosting with\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 full control. UnisonBridge is designed to be the definitive open-source answer.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ## 2. VISION STATEMENT\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 "Any USB device, on any machine, accessible from any other machine on the network \'97\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 without configuration expertise, without vendor lock-in, and without compromising\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 security."\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ## 3. TARGET USERS & PERSONAS\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ### Persona 1 \'97 Alex, the Homelab Engineer\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Role:** Self-hosted enthusiast running Proxmox with multiple LXC containers and VMs\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Environment:** Linux-primary, Windows VMs, Raspberry Pi servers\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Pain Point:** Cannot easily pass USB devices (Zigbee dongle, license key, USB drive)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   from host to containers without complex udev rules and manual command-line work\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Goal:** Single web UI to see all USB devices across all nodes and connect them\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   with one click\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Technical Level:** High \'97 comfortable with command line, systemd, Docker\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ### Persona 2 \'97 Maria, the Lab Administrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Role:** IT admin for a hardware testing lab with 20 workstations\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Environment:** Mixed Linux/Windows, test devices include USB oscilloscopes,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   serial adapters, security dongles, embedded debug probes\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Pain Point:** Engineers must physically walk to machines to plug in devices or\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   fight over shared hardware; no audit trail for who used what\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Goal:** Centrally manage which engineer has access to which device; see real-time\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   status; get alerts when devices disconnect\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Technical Level:** Medium \'97 knows networking, not a kernel developer\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ### Persona 3 \'97 Devon, the DevOps/Embedded Developer\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Role:** Firmware developer flashing and debugging microcontrollers\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Environment:** WSL2 on Windows, remote Linux build servers\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Pain Point:** USB debug probes (J-Link, ST-LINK, CMSIS-DAP) are not accessible\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   from WSL2 without manual usbipd commands; breaks CI/CD pipelines\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Goal:** Automate USB device forwarding into WSL2 with persistent profiles;\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   integrate with GitHub Actions\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Technical Level:** High \'97 knows CI/CD, comfortable with Rust/Python\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ### Persona 4 \'97 Sam, the Remote Worker\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Role:** Software engineer working from home\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Environment:** Home workstation + remote office server\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Pain Point:** Security dongle is physically at the office; must VPN in and\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   somehow access the USB device remotely\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Goal:** Secure remote access to USB devices over WireGuard/Tailscale\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Technical Level:** Medium-High\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ### Persona 5 \'97 Jordan, the Non-Technical End User\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Role:** Creative professional using a USB audio interface and MIDI controller\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Environment:** macOS primary, sometimes needs devices on a Windows machine\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Pain Point:** Cannot share audio interface between machines without physically\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   re-plugging cables\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Goal:** Simple one-click sharing with no terminal commands\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Technical Level:** Low \'97 needs a GUI that explains what is happening\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ## 4. PROBLEM STATEMENT\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 USB devices are physically tethered to single machines. When distributed teams,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 homelab setups, containerized environments, or remote work scenarios require access\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 to physical USB hardware from machines other than the one it is plugged into, the\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 current options are:\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 1. **Raw USB/IP (Linux only):** Powerful but requires kernel module management,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19    manual CLI commands, no GUI, no auto-discovery, no security, no compatibility\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19    warnings, fails for isochronous devices on typical networks.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 2. **usbipd-win (Windows):** Excellent for WSL2 but no GUI, no multi-machine\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19    orchestration, no compatibility analysis.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 3. **VirtualHere/FlexiHub:** Commercial, closed-source, expensive at scale, no\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19    open API, vendor lock-in.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 4. **RDP/SPICE USB Redirection:** Tied to remote desktop sessions, not general\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19    purpose.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **UnisonBridge solves this** by providing an open-source, self-hosted, cross-platform\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 orchestration layer with a web UI, zero-config discovery, compatibility intelligence,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 security, and virtual device support.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ## 5. CORE USE CASES\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-ID | Use Case | Primary Actor | Description |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 |-------|----------|---------------|-------------|\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-01 | Share USB device to another machine | Lab User | User sees all USB devices across all agents in the dashboard and connects one to their machine with drag-and-drop |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-02 | Auto-discover agents on network | System | When a new agent starts, it announces itself via mDNS; orchestrator adds it automatically |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-03 | Detect incompatible device before connection | System | Before attempting to share a webcam, system scores compatibility and warns user about isochronous issues |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-04 | Route isochronous audio via PipeWire instead | System | When USB audio device fails compatibility check, system offers to create PipeWire virtual sink instead |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-05 | View live logs for a failed connection | Lab Admin | Admin opens log viewer, filters by device, sees ENOSR error with automated suggestion |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-06 | Create virtual webcam from RTSP stream | Power User | User creates v4l2loopback virtual camera fed by GStreamer pipeline; appears as real webcam to applications |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-07 | Auto-connect device on agent restart | System | Policy rule causes device to automatically bind and attach to target machine when both agents reconnect |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-08 | Restrict device access by user role | Admin | Admin configures RBAC so only "Lab Technicians" group can attach USB storage devices |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-09 | Forward USB device to WSL2 | Developer | Developer uses UnisonBridge agent on Windows to forward debug probe into WSL2 |\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 | UC-10 | Monitor all connections from Prometheus | Admin | Admin scrapes /metrics endpoint to track device count, error rates, latency in Grafana |\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ## 6. USER STORIES\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ### CATEGORY A: Device Discovery (US-001 to US-010)\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-001: Auto-discover agents via mDNS**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** system administrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** the UnisonBridge orchestrator to automatically discover all agents on my\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   local network using mDNS/DNS-SD without any manual IP configuration\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I do not need to manually register each machine in the system\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: When an agent starts, it announces `_unisonbridge-agent._tcp.local` within\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     5 seconds of startup\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: The orchestrator receives the mDNS announcement and adds the machine to the\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     MachineRegistry within 10 seconds\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: The web UI displays the newly discovered machine in the dashboard without\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     requiring a page refresh\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: If the agent stops, the orchestrator marks the machine as offline within\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     30 seconds (heartbeat timeout)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: mDNS TXT record includes: version, os, hostname, agent_port, api_port\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** High\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 1\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-002: Enumerate USB devices on agent startup**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** lab engineer\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** every USB device currently connected to a machine to appear in the\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   dashboard immediately when the agent starts\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I have an accurate inventory of available hardware without manual scanning\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Agent enumerates all USB devices using libusb within 3 seconds of startup\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Each device is reported with: idVendor, idProduct, manufacturer string,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     product string, serial number, bcdUSB, device class, subclass, protocol\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Interface-level class codes are inspected when device-level class is 0x00\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: All devices appear in the web UI within 5 seconds of agent startup\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Devices with no serial number are assigned a stable pseudo-ID based on\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     bus topology + VID:PID\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** High\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 1\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-003: Detect USB hotplug events in real time**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** lab administrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** the system to detect when a USB device is plugged in or unplugged from\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   any agent machine and immediately update the dashboard\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** the device inventory is always accurate and I can act on new devices\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   without refreshing the page\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Agent receives hotplug notification within 500ms of physical device insertion\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     on Linux (via libudev), Windows (SetupDI), macOS (IOKit)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: `device.added` WebSocket event is emitted to the UI within 2 seconds of\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     physical insertion\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: `device.removed` WebSocket event is emitted within 2 seconds of physical\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     removal\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: If a device that is currently shared is physically unplugged, the connection\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     state transitions to ERROR with error message "device removed from server"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: The dashboard updates without requiring any user interaction\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** High\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 1\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-004: Display USB device class and type in human-readable form**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** non-technical user\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to see USB devices described in plain English (e.g., "USB Audio Device",\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   "Mass Storage Drive", "Security Dongle") rather than hex class codes\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I can identify devices without needing to understand USB specifications\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Device class code 0x03 is displayed as "HID \'97 Keyboard/Mouse/Gamepad"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Device class code 0x08 is displayed as "Mass Storage"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Device class code 0x01 is displayed as "Audio Device (USB Audio Class)"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Device class code 0x0E is displayed as "Video Device (Webcam/Capture)"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Vendor ID + Product ID is resolved to manufacturer and product name using\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     the bundled usb.ids database\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC6: Unknown devices display raw hex codes with tooltip explaining they are\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     unrecognized\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** High\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 1\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-005: Display device compatibility score before connection**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** lab user\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to see a compatibility rating (COMPATIBLE / PARTIAL / LIMITED /\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   INCOMPATIBLE) for each USB device before I attempt to share it\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I know in advance whether the connection will work reliably over USB/IP\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Score 90-100 displays green badge "COMPATIBLE" with tooltip "Bulk/interrupt\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     transfers only. Works excellently over USB/IP."\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Score 60-89 displays yellow badge "PARTIAL" with tooltip "May work on low-\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     latency LAN. Will fail over WAN or with >5ms RTT."\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Score 30-59 displays orange badge "LIMITED" with tooltip "Uses isochronous\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     transfers. USB/IP will likely fail. Consider virtual device layer."\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Score 0-29 displays red badge "INCOMPATIBLE" with tooltip "Fundamentally\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     incompatible with USB/IP. Use alternative protocol."\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Compatibility score is computed from: class code, endpoint transfer types,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     declared isochronous bandwidth, historical success rate for this VID:PID\cf0 \cb1 \
