\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: When a connection is interrupted (TCP reset), agent waits 5 seconds then\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     attempts to reconnect\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Agent retries with exponential backoff: 5s, 10s, 20s, 40s, max 120s\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: After 10 consecutive failed reconnect attempts, connection status is set\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     to FAILED and user is notified\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: When device reappears (e.g., after agent restart), auto-connect policy\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     triggers re-attachment if configured\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: All reconnect attempts are logged with timestamp and failure reason\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** High\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 2\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-016: Create auto-connect policy for a device**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** developer who needs a debug probe always attached to a specific machine\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to define a policy that automatically attaches a specific device to a\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   specific machine whenever both agents are online\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I never have to manually reconnect my debug probe after reboots\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Policy creation UI allows selecting: device (by VID:PID or serial),\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     target machine, priority (if device is requested by multiple policies)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Policy is stored in orchestrator database and survives restarts\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: When device appears on server agent and target agent is online, orchestrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     automatically executes bind + attach within 10 seconds\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: If target agent is offline, orchestrator queues the connection and executes\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     it when the target agent comes online\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Policy can be paused, deleted, or have a time window (e.g., only weekdays\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     9am-6pm)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** High\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 2\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-017: Handle device conflict when two users request same device**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** lab administrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** the system to handle the case where two users simultaneously request\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   the same USB device\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** there are no race conditions and one user gets a clear error message\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Orchestrator uses optimistic locking on device state; only one connection\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     can be created per device at a time\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Second user to request the device receives error: "Device [name] is already\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     attached to [machine]. Request access from the current user or wait."\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Second user can join a queue: "Notify me when this device is available"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: When device is released, queued user receives browser notification and\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     dashboard toast: "[Device] is now available"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Admin can force-detach a device from its current user (with audit log entry)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Medium\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 3\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-018: Force-detach a device as administrator**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** system administrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to forcibly disconnect a device from whatever machine it is currently\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   attached to\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I can reclaim devices for maintenance, emergency use, or policy enforcement\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: "Force Detach" button is visible to users with Admin role on all connections\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Clicking "Force Detach" shows: "This will immediately disconnect [user]'s\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     session with [device]. They will lose any unsaved work. Continue?"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Force detach sends `cmd.detach` to client agent without waiting for\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     user confirmation from the current session owner\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Current session owner sees dashboard notification: "Your connection to\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     [device] was disconnected by [admin username]"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Audit log records: timestamp, admin who forced detach, device, machine,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     previous owner, reason (optional text field)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Medium\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 3\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-019: Share a device to a specific WSL2 distribution**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** Windows developer using WSL2\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to share a USB device from my Windows host directly into a specific\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   WSL2 Linux distribution\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** my Linux development environment in WSL2 can use physical USB devices\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Windows agent detects available WSL2 distributions via `wsl --list`\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Connection wizard on Windows offers "WSL2 Target" option alongside network\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     machine targets\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Selected WSL2 distribution is listed with its Linux version and USB/IP\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     kernel module availability\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Agent executes `usbipd attach --wsl [distro] --busid [id]` and reports\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     success/failure\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Persistent auto-attach profile can be configured for WSL2 targets with\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     the same policy system as network targets\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** High\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 2\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-020: Attach device from Proxmox LXC container**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** Proxmox administrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** the UnisonBridge agent running inside an LXC container to be able to\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   attach remote USB devices as though they were passed through locally\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** containerized applications can use remote USB devices\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Agent inside LXC container can load vhci-hcd kernel module (requires host\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     to have it loaded and LXC config to allow it)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Setup guide documents required LXC config: `lxc.cgroup2.devices.allow`\cf0 \cb1 \
