\cf3 \cb19 **US-048: Stream virtual camera via WebRTC for browser preview**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** user\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to preview a virtual camera stream directly in the web dashboard\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   without installing any software\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I can verify the virtual camera is working before using it in\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   an application\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Device detail drawer for virtual cameras has "Preview" button\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Clicking Preview opens an embedded WebRTC video player in the dashboard\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Preview stream uses mediamtx server running alongside the orchestrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     to serve WebRTC from the GStreamer pipeline\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Preview works in Chrome, Firefox, Safari without plugins\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Preview has <3 second latency on local network\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC6: Preview auto-stops after 60 seconds to conserve bandwidth (with option\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     to continue)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Low\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 4\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-049: List all virtual devices in dashboard**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** user\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to see all currently active virtual devices in a dedicated section\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   of the dashboard\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I have a complete picture of both physical and virtual devices\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: "Virtual Devices" section in sidebar navigation opens dedicated panel\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Panel lists all virtual devices with: type icon (audio/video/HID/storage),\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     name, source machine, target machine, status, uptime\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Virtual devices created by other users are visible (with read-only info)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     to Operators; Admins can manage all\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Clicking a virtual device shows detail panel with stream health metrics\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Empty state shows: "No virtual devices. Click '+' to create one."\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Medium\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 4\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-050: Persist virtual device configuration across restarts**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** user who creates virtual devices regularly\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** virtual device configurations to be saved and automatically\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   recreated when the orchestrator and agents restart\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I do not have to manually recreate virtual devices after reboots\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Virtual device configuration is stored in `virtual_devices` table\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     in orchestrator SQLite database\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: On orchestrator startup, it reads all active virtual device configs\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     and sends creation commands to relevant agents\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: If an agent is offline when recreating, the orchestrator retries\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     when the agent comes online\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: User can mark a virtual device as "persistent" or "session-only"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     (session-only is destroyed when user logs out)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Persistent virtual devices survive orchestrator restarts without\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     user intervention\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Medium\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 4\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ### CATEGORY F: Diagnostics & Logging (US-051 to US-060)\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-051: Collect kernel USB/IP logs from all agents**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** system administrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** kernel-level USB/IP logs (journalctl -k, dmesg) to be collected\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   from all Linux agents and viewable in the central log viewer\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I can diagnose kernel-level USB issues without SSH-ing into each machine\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Linux agent reads from journalctl kernel messages matching 'usbip|vhci'\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     using journald socket interface\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Agent streams new log entries to orchestrator via WebSocket as they occur\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Log entries include: agent hostname, timestamp, kernel facility, message\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Log viewer can filter to show only kernel logs from a specific agent\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Agent config allows disabling kernel log collection:\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     `kernel_logs_enabled = false`\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** High\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 3\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-052: Collect Windows Event Log USB events from Windows agents**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** system administrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** USB-related Windows Event Log entries from Windows agents to be\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   forwarded to the central log viewer\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I can see Windows USB driver events alongside Linux kernel logs\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Windows agent reads from Event Log: System log, USB event sources\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     (usbhub, usbport, etc.)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Agent filters for events related to usbipd-win service and USB device\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     connect/disconnect\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Windows event log entries are normalized to the same log format as\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     Linux kernel messages\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Windows agent collects: Event ID, Source, Level, TimeCreated, Message\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Log viewer shows Windows events color-coded differently from Linux events\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Medium\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 3\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-053: Export log data for external analysis**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** developer\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to export log data from the orchestrator in machine-readable formats\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I can feed it into external log analysis tools or include it in\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   bug reports\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: GET /api/v1/logs?machine=<id>&device=<id>&level=ERROR&from=<iso8601>&\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     to=<iso8601>&format=json returns filtered log entries as JSON array\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: format=csv returns CSV with headers: timestamp, level, machine, device,\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     message, raw_data\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: format=ndjson returns newline-delimited JSON for streaming log processing\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Maximum export size is 100,000 entries per request; pagination via\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     cursor parameter\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Export includes all metadata: agent version, kernel version, OS type\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Low\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 3\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-054: Set log retention period**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** administrator managing disk space\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to configure how long log entries are retained before automatic deletion\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** log storage does not grow unbounded on the orchestrator machine\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: `log_retention_days = 30` config option in orchestrator (default: 30)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Daily cleanup job runs at 02:00 UTC and deletes log entries older than\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     retention period\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Audit log has separate retention: `audit_log_retention_days = 365` (default)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Admin can trigger manual cleanup: POST /api/v1/admin/cleanup-logs\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Dashboard shows current log storage size and estimated days until next cleanup\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Low\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 3\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-055: Track connection latency over time**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** performance-conscious user\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to see how USB/IP connection latency changes over time for a\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   specific device connection\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I can identify if network conditions are degrading and correlate\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   with device issues\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Agent measures round-trip time for each USBIP_CMD_SUBMIT / USBIP_RET_SUBMIT\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     pair and reports to orchestrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Orchestrator stores latency samples in time-series format (last 24 hours\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     at 1-minute granularity)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Connection detail panel shows latency sparkline chart (last 60 minutes)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Latency percentiles are shown: p50, p95, p99\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: Alert rule can be configured: if p95 latency > Xms for Y minutes, send\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     dashboard notification\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Medium\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 3\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-056: Alert on agent going offline**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** system administrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to receive an alert when any agent goes offline unexpectedly\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I can investigate and restore connectivity before users notice issues\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Orchestrator detects agent offline when heartbeat is missed for 30 seconds\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: Dashboard notification: "[machine] went offline at [time]"\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: If agent was serving active connections, those connections are marked as\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     FAILED and affected users are notified\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC4: Alert can be configured to send webhook notification to external systems\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     (Slack, PagerDuty): `alert_webhook_url = "https://hooks.slack.com/..."` in config\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC5: When agent comes back online, "Agent reconnected" notification is shown\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Priority:** Medium\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Phase:** 3\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 ---\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\cf3 \cb19 **US-057: Debug mode with verbose USB/IP protocol logging**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **As a** developer debugging USB/IP issues\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **I want** to enable verbose logging that captures every URB submission and\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   response for a specific device connection\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **So that** I can diagnose subtle timing or protocol issues at the packet level\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 - **Acceptance Criteria:**\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC1: Agent config accepts `debug_usb_protocol = true` to enable verbose logging\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC2: When enabled, every USBIP_CMD_SUBMIT and USBIP_RET_SUBMIT is logged with:\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19     sequence number, device ID, endpoint, direction, data length, latency\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19   - AC3: Verbose log entries are tagged `level: DEBUG` and filtered out of normal\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 log view unless DEBUG filter\cf0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

