\f9\b \cf20 \cb19 \strokec20 ## 1. ARCHITECTURE OPTIONS CONSIDERED
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\

\f9\b \cf20 \cb19 \strokec20 ### Option A: Monolithic Server with Embedded Agents (Rejected)
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Description:\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf3 \strokec2  Single binary that runs on every machine, acts as both agent\cf0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \cb19 and orchestrator. Peers communicate directly via P2P mesh.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Pros:\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Simple deployment (one binary, no central server)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  No single point of failure\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Cons:\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  No central state: impossible to show all devices in one UI\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Each node must know about all other nodes (O(n\'b2) connections)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  No central policy enforcement point\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Extremely difficult to implement RBAC without central authority\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  UI would need to aggregate from all nodes (slow, inconsistent)\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Verdict: REJECTED.\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf3 \strokec2  Central state management and single-pane-of-glass UI\cf0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \cb19 require a central coordinator.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 ---\cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf20 \cb19 \strokec20 ### Option B: Cloud-Hosted Controller (Rejected)
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Description:\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf3 \strokec2  Orchestrator runs in the cloud (AWS, Azure). Agents connect\cf0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \cb19 outbound to cloud controller. Similar to FlexiHub's architecture.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Pros:\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Easy NAT traversal\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  High availability by default\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Cons:\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  USB/IP data cannot reasonably flow through cloud (too much latency)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Privacy concerns: USB device metadata in cloud\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Requires internet connectivity\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Defeats self-hosted, open-source philosophy\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Monthly cost\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Verdict: REJECTED.\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf3 \strokec2  UnisonBridge is self-hosted by design.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 ---\cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf20 \cb19 \strokec20 ### Option C: Three-Tier Self-Hosted Architecture (CHOSEN)
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Description:\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf3 \strokec2  \cf0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Tier 1: Agent daemon on every machine (data plane edge)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Tier 2: Orchestrator server on one machine (control plane center)\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Tier 3: Web UI (presentation layer)\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \cb19 USB/IP data flows directly between agents (peer-to-peer, bypassing orchestrator).\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf3 \cb19 Orchestrator handles only coordination, state, and API.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Pros:\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Central state enables single-pane-of-glass UI\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  USB data performance not limited by orchestrator bandwidth\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  RBAC, audit logging, policy enforcement centralized\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Self-hosted: no external dependencies\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Scales to 100+ agents\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Orchestrator failure does not interrupt existing USB connections\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Cons:\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Orchestrator is a single point of failure for new connections\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  Requires dedicated machine or container for orchestrator\cf0 \cb1 \
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 -\cf3 \strokec2  More complex than pure P2P\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 **\cf3 \strokec2 Verdict: CHOSEN.\cf24 \strokec24 **
\f7\b0 \cf3 \strokec2  Best balance of capability, self-hosted ethos, and performance.\cf0 \cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf24 \cb19 \strokec24 ---\cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f9\b \cf20 \cb19 \strokec20 ## 2. RECOMMENDED ARCHITECTURE: THREE-TIER
\f7\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \
