## 6. TECHNOLOGY STACK DECISIONS\
\
### ADR-001: Rust for Agent and Orchestrator\
\
**Decision:** Use Rust for both the agent daemon and the orchestrator server.\
\
**Rationale:**\
- Memory safety without garbage collector \'97 critical for long-running daemons\
- tokio async runtime handles thousands of concurrent WebSocket connections\
  efficiently with minimal CPU overhead\
- Cross-compilation to Linux (x86_64, ARM64, ARM), Windows (x86_64),\
  macOS (x86_64, Apple Silicon) from a single codebase\
- Binary size: typically 5-15MB (versus 60MB+ for Go, 100MB+ for Python)\
- Shared types between agent and orchestrator crates (Cargo workspace)\
- Memory safety eliminates entire classes of security vulnerabilities\
  (buffer overflows, use-after-free) that have historically affected USB/IP\
\
**Trade-offs:**\
- Steeper learning curve than Go or Python\
- Longer initial compilation time\
- Smaller contributor pool than Python/Go\
\
**Mitigation:** Provide Docker dev container; document Rust learning resources;\
design APIs to be simple even if internals are complex.\
\
---\
\
### ADR-002: Axum for REST API and WebSocket Server\
\
**Decision:** Use tokio-rs/axum for the orchestrator HTTP/WebSocket server.\
\
**Rationale:**\
- Built on tokio (same runtime as agent) \'97 no context switching overhead\
- First-class WebSocket support via tokio-tungstenite\
- Excellent middleware composition (tower middleware stack)\
- Type-safe extractors for request validation\
- Serves static files (web UI) from same binary\
\
**Alternatives Considered:**\
- actix-web: Higher performance in benchmarks but more complex; different\
  async model can cause issues with tokio compatibility\
- warp: Simpler but less ergonomic for complex routing\
- axum chosen for balance of ergonomics, performance, and ecosystem\
\
---\
\
### ADR-003: SQLite via SQLx for State Persistence\
\
**Decision:** Use SQLite as the orchestrator database via the sqlx crate\
with compile-time query verification.\
\
**Rationale:**\
- Zero-configuration embedded database \'97 no separate database server required\
- WAL (Write-Ahead Logging) mode provides crash safety and concurrent reads\
- Compile-time query verification catches SQL errors at build time\
- Schema can migrate to PostgreSQL for larger deployments (same SQLx API)\
- Single file backup: `cp unisonbridge.db unisonbridge.db.bak`\
- Sufficient for 1,000 devices and 200 connections (tested)\
\
**Trade-offs:**\
- Not suitable for horizontal scaling (multiple orchestrator instances)\
  sharing the same database\
- Performance ceiling around 10,000 concurrent writes/second\
\
**Mitigation:** Document PostgreSQL migration path for large deployments;\
design schema to be portable from day one.\
\
---\
\
### ADR-004: React 19 + TypeScript for Web UI\
\
**Decision:** Use React 19 with TypeScript, built with Vite.\
\
**Rationale:**\
- React's component model suits the device card / machine card UI paradigm\
- TypeScript provides type safety matching the Rust backend's type-safe API\
- Vite: sub-second hot module replacement during development\
- Large ecosystem: TanStack Query for server state, dnd-kit for drag-and-drop,\
  shadcn/ui for accessible components, xterm.js for log terminal\
- Wide developer familiarity reduces contributor onboarding friction\
\
**Alternatives Considered:**\
- Vue 3: Excellent but smaller ecosystem for our specific needs\
- SvelteKit: Excellent performance but even smaller ecosystem\
- HTMX: Too limited for real-time WebSocket-driven dashboard\
\
---\
\
### ADR-005: mDNS/DNS-SD for Zero-Config Discovery\
\
**Decision:** Use mDNS/DNS-SD (via mdns-sd Rust crate on agent,\
Avahi on Linux, native Bonjour on macOS) for agent discovery.\
\
**Rationale:**\
- Zero configuration: agents discover each other without any IP configuration\
- Same technology as Apple's Bonjour (used by AirPrint, Chromecast, etc.)\
- Works on Linux (Avahi), macOS (native), Windows (mdns-sd crate)\
- TXT records carry metadata (version, OS, ports) without extra roundtrip\
- Graceful degradation: unicast fallback when mDNS is blocked\
\
**Trade-offs:**\
- Only works within single L2 broadcast domain (subnet)\
- Some managed switches/firewalls block mDNS multicast\
\
**Mitigation:** Unicast registration fallback; WireGuard overlay documentation;\
enterprise relay server component (Phase 5)\
\
---\
